add_6787_f027 27 53 JS Jul 24, 2012 Work on spherical triangles. On this page there are references to both Regiomontanus and Clavius, who both gave a version of the theorem given here. The reference to Regiomontanus is to his De triangulis omnimodis libri quinque (Regiomontanus [1464], 1533, 1561, Prop V.2) . (For another reference to the same proposition, see also Add MS 6782 f. 490 .) The reference to Clavius is to his Triangula sphærica in Triangula rectilinea, atque sphaerica (Clavius 1586, Prop 58) . Harriot translates Clavius's statement into symbols for the particular triangle $ dab $ shown in his diagram. He then goes on to prove that the versed sine of $ ad - db $ is greater than the versed sine of $ ab $. For another version of this page, see Add MS 6787 f. 51 . (5. add_6787_f031 31 61 JS Jul 24, 2012 The reference on this page is to Proposition 21 from Chapter 19 of Viète's Variorum responsorum liber VIII (Viete 1593d, Chapter 19, Prop 21) . Immediately after the statement of the proposition, Viète gave the following statement, under the heading Syntomon. In modern notation this statement may be written as: $ 1: 2\sin(a) = \sin(b):\cos(a - b) + \cos(a + b) $. This is the ratio Harriot has written next to diagram 1, where both angles are acute. The other diagrams are for cases where one or both the angles are obtuse. Vieta lib. 8. resp. pag. 39. Viète, Responsorum liber VIII. Syntomon
add_6787_f031 31 61 JS Jul 24, 2012 Vieta lib. 8. resp. pag. 39. Viète, Responsorum liber VIII. Syntomon in alia charta in another sheet
add_6787_f031 31 61 JS Jul 24, 2012 Vieta lib. 8. resp. pag. 39. Viète, Responsorum liber VIII. Syntomon Quæ per factionem sub sinibus peripherieriarum et adplicationem ad sinum totum exurgunt, eadem opere additionis vel subductionis præsto sunt. What appears from a combination of the sine of the arcs, dividing the sine of the total, is also shown by the operations of addition and subtraction.
add_6787_f031 31 61 JS Jul 24, 2012 Vieta lib. 8. resp. pag. 39. Viète, Responsorum liber VIII. Syntomon $ ab $, una peripheria $ bc $, altera peripheria $ dc $, differentia $ abc $, aggregatum &c. $ ab $ is one arc, $ bc $ the other. $ dc $ is the difference, $ abc $ the sum.
add_6787_f031 31 61 JS Jul 24, 2012 Vieta lib. 8. resp. pag. 39. Viète, Responsorum liber VIII. Syntomon Hæc quarta analogia est re eadem cum secunda. porro, prima et tertia analogiæ reducuntur ad unam si quartus terminus ita notetur. This fourth ratio is the same thing as the second. Further, the first and third ratios are reduced to one if the fourth term is written thus.
add_6787_f031 31 61 JS Jul 24, 2012 Vieta lib. 8. resp. pag. 39. Viète, Responsorum liber VIII. Syntomon Nota Quando una peripheria est maior quadranti ut $ bc $ est 3, et 4, diagrammati; summatur eius residuum ad semicirculum. Et tum operatio erit secundum primum vel secundum casum. Quare hoc modo sunt duo tantummodo casus. Note. When one arc is greater than a quadrant, as $ bc $ is in the 3rd and 4th diagrams, there are taken their residuals from a semicircle. And then the operation will be as the first or second case. Therefore by this method there are only two cases.

add_6787_f034 34 67 JS Jul 24, 2012 (9. Casuum Limitatio cum designatione adcomodum Determination of cases with a useful specification Animadvertendum quod in superioribus investigationibus analogiarum sive casuum, ubi latera $ ad $ et $ db $ signantur \le \le; debeat etiam intelligi signata \ge \ge. Quoniam si sint eiusdem affectionis sive utrique minora quadrantibus, sive maiora; non variatur inde illatio neque casus. Hinc in 6 notatis casibus positi trianguli, sunt 9 variationes signorum ut sequitur. It is to be noted that in the above investigations of ratios, or cases, where the sides $ ab $ and $ db $ are marked with \le, \le, respectively, it is also to be understood that they could be marked with \ge, \ge, respectively. Because they have the same relationship, whether both less than a quadrant, or greater; therefore the result does not vary, nor the cases. Here in the 6 denoted cases of the supposed triangle, there are 9 variations.
add_6787_f034 34 67 JS Jul 24, 2012 (9. Besides those nine, there are three other variations; more are not given, but these are impossible.

add_6787_f221 221 440 JS Jul 25, 2012 At the end of Chapter XIX of Variorum responsorum liber VIII (1593), under the heading 'ALIUD', Viète listed sixteen propositions connecting sines, tangents, and secants (Viete 1593d, Chapter 19, ALIUD) . In the first edition of the Responsorum, the pages were numbered only on the recto side. However, the pagination went badly wrong, so that in Chapter XIX we have the sequence: 37, 38, 39, 38. This sometimes makes it difficult to follow Harriot's references correctly. Here it seems that he has seen the number '38' on the right-hand (recto) page, and thus inferred that the left-hand (verso) page must be 37v, whereas it is in fact 39v. In the 1646 edition of Viète's Opera mathematica the sixteen propositions are to be found on pages 412–413. On this and the following pages, Harriot worked through the sixteen propositions systematically. On this page he lists the first six. Note that for Harriot, as for Viète, trigonometrical relationships arose from astronomy. Thus the concepts of sine, tangent, and secant related not to angles defined by a pair of lines meeting at a point, but to arcs of a circle with a given radius, and therefore only by implication to the angles subtended by them. At the top of the page Harriot listed the relevant quantities: sine, tangent, secant, radius (or whole sine), and the symbols he regularly used for them. The equivalent names used by Viète were sinus, prosinus, transinuosa, totus. Harriot had no words for cosine, cotangent, or coseceant. Where we would use 'cosine', for example, he spoke of the sine of the complement. Thus he wrote $ \upsilon $ BC for sine(arc BC) but $ \upsilon $ BC for the sine of the complement of BC, that is, cosine(BC). vieta in lib. 8. respons. pag. 37. proportionalia Viète, in Responsorum liber VIII, page 37, proportionals

add_6787_f372 372 742 De ellipsi. On the ellipse Theorema
add_6787_f372 372 742 JS May 30, 2012 De ellipsi. On the ellipse Si quotlibet lineis ordinatim applicatis ad diametrum circuli, aliæ numero et quantitate æquales similiter applicentur ad similes partes lineæ maioris minoris data diametro circuli: termini illarum linearum sunt in ellipsi. If any number of ordinate lines are dropped to the diameter of a circle, that number of other lines, equal in quantity and similarly applied to similar parts of lines greater or less than the given diameter of a circe, then the ends of those lines are on an ellipse.
add_6787_f372 372 742 JS May 30, 2012 De ellipsi. On the ellipse Sit diameter circuli $ dc $. lineæ ordinatim applicatæ $ ab $ et $ ef $. sit etiam linea maior quam $ dc $ $ δx $ cui applicentur ad angulos rectos $ αβ $ et $ εθ $ æquales $ ab $ et $ ef $ circuli. fiat ud $ δx $ ad $ dc $ ita $ δβ $ ad $ db $ et $ δθ $ ad $ df $. Quod etiam fit si utraque lineæ similter dividantur et ad utraque partes similes et similiter sitas æquales lineæ ordinatim applicentur. Dico quod puncta $ α $ et $ ε $ termini linearum $ αθ $ et $ εθ $ sunt in ellipsi. Quoniam ex hypothesi Ergo: per 21, prop: primi Apollonij, puncta $ α $ et $ ε $ sunt in ellipsi. quod demonstrare oportuit. Let the diameter of the circle be $ dc $, and the ordinate lines $ ab $ and $ ef $; also let the line greater than $ dc $ be $ δx $, to which are applied at right angles $ αβ $ and $ εθ $ euqal to the lines $ ab $ and $ ef $ in the circle. But thus, as $ δx $ is to $ dc $ so is $ δβ $ to $ db $ and $ δθ $ to $ df $. Which also happens if the two lines $ dc $ et $ δx $ are similarly divided and to both parts, similar and similarly situated, equal ordinate lines are applied. I say that the points $ α $ and $ ε $, the ends of the lines $ αθ $ and $ εθ $, are on an ellipse. Because from the hypothesis: Therefore, by Proposition 21 of the first Book of Apollonius, the points $ α $ et $ ε $ are on an ellipse; which was to be demonstrated.

Construct $ ad $, whcih will cut the circumference $ he $ in the point $ q $. Construct $ ql $ extended, parallel to $ ad $ and $ ag $; whcih will cut the circumference $ gh $ at $ r $. Construct $ ar $ extended, and it will cut $ es $ in the point $ s $. I say that the point $ s $ is on the hyperbolea. (From the demonstration in B.1.)

add_6787_f566v 566v 1131 JS Feb 8, 2013 Si fuerint magnitudines continue decrescentes proportionaliter in infinitum primum, est media proportionalis inter differentium primum et secundum, et compositum ex omnibus in infinitum. If there are magnitudes continually proportional, decreasing indefinitely, the first is the mean proportional between the difference of the first and the second, and the sum of all of them infinitely.

add_6787_f568 568 1134 JS May 26, 2012 This page refers to Proposition 53 from Book I of Apollonius, as edited by Commandino in Conicorum libri quattuor (Apollonius 1566) . Proposition (Problem) I.53 is an extension of Proposition (Problem) I.52. There is also a reference to the equivalent construction for an ellipse, as demonstrated by Commandino in Pappi Alexandrini mathematicae collectiones (1588). The construction, and Commandino's commentary on it, are to be found on pages 320v–321.

add_6787_f568 568 1134 JS May 27, 2012 1) fiat $ ai = ac $ et: periferia agatur $ bei $ secabit $ ac $ productam in $ e $. fiat: $ ap = \frac{ae}{2} $ et: $ aq = ap $ agantur $ ap $ et $ aq $ productæ et sunt asymptotæ hyperboles let $ ai = ac $, and take the circumference $ bei $, which will cut $ ac $ produced at $ e $; let $ ap = \frac{ae}{2} $, and $ aq = ap $. Taking $ ap $ et $ aq $ produced, these will be the asymptotes of the hyperbolas.
add_6787_f568 568 1134 JS May 27, 2012 2) fiat $ dr = dq $ Agatur periferia $ rsp $ sit $ ds $ ad angulos rectos fiat: $ dt = ds $ et; $ du = dt $ agatur $ ut $ secetur ut per medium in $ l $ et fiat $ kd = dl $ Dico quod $ kl $, est axis et puncta $ l $, est vertex sectionis. let $ dr = dq $; take the circumference $ rsp $, and set $ ds $ at right angles. Let $ dt = ds $ and $ du = dt $; taking $ ut $, it will be cut in the middle at $ l $; and let $ kd = dl $. I say that $ kl $ is the axis, and the point $ l $ is the vertex of the section.
